        Selling Your Home Privately in Queensland 2027: What FSBO Sellers Need to Know
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Selling privately is legal in Queensland, but it carries legal obligations, pricing challenges, and negotiation risks that most FSBO sellers underestimate before they start.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The appeal of selling privately is straightforward: avoid paying commission. On a $1.2 million Brisbane inner-east property, a commission of 2 to 2.5 per cent represents $24,000 to $30,000. That is real money, and it is reasonable to ask whether you can replicate what an agent does well enough to keep it. The honest answer is that some sellers can, and many cannot. This article explains what you are actually taking on when you sell privately in Queensland, so you can make that assessment based on facts rather than optimism.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a private sale involves legally</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, there is no law requiring a licensed real estate agent to sell residential property. What the law does require is that the sale itself complies with the Property Law Act 1974 and associated legislation, and that you meet every seller disclosure obligation regardless of whether an agent is involved.</p>

      <p>You will need a Queensland-compliant contract of sale. This is not something you write yourself. You need a solicitor or conveyancer to prepare it, and they will need to conduct the conveyancing through to settlement regardless of how you sell. Budget for conveyancing costs of $1,500 to $2,500 typically, similar to what you would pay if using an agent.</p>

      <p>You must also provide a disclosure statement to the buyer. Queensland's seller disclosure obligations require you to disclose matters such as whether the property is affected by a statutory charge, whether it is in a community titles scheme, whether there is a registered easement or encumbrance, and whether the property has been used for an unlawful purpose. Getting this wrong creates liability. Your solicitor handles this, but you as the seller are responsible for providing accurate information.</p>

      <p>Pool safety and smoke alarm compliance sit with you as the seller, not the agent. A pool safety certificate is required before settlement in Queensland unless you negotiate a pool safety inspection condition into the contract. Smoke alarms must be interconnected and photoelectric in owner-occupied properties sold from January 2022. These requirements apply whether you are selling through an agent or privately.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Pricing accurately without agent data access</h2>
      <p>One of the most underestimated challenges in a private sale is pricing. Most sellers believe they know what their property is worth because they have been watching the market, but the data private sellers can access publicly lags by several months and excludes off-market sales entirely. Agents have access to real-time comparable sales data, buyer feedback from active campaigns, and knowledge of what competing properties are actually achieving versus what they are asking. That information gap is significant.</p>

      <p>Overpricing is the most common private sale mistake and it is costly. A property that launches at $1.35 million when comparable sales suggest $1.22 million will sit on the market. Extended days on market signal to buyers that something is wrong, even if nothing is. When you eventually reduce the price, buyers who have been watching apply their own discount on top of the reduction because they perceive you as a motivated or distressed seller. The compounding effect of an overpriced launch frequently costs more than the commission you were trying to save.</p>

      <p>To price accurately as a private seller, you should commission a registered valuation from a certified practising valuer before you launch. A valuation costs $400 to $700 and gives you a defensible market value based on actual comparable sales. This is money well spent, and it also provides a reference point in buyer negotiations.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to get on realestate.com.au as a private seller</h2>
      <p>Realestate.com.au and Domain do not accept listings directly from private sellers. Both portals require that listings are submitted by a licensed real estate agent. This is a significant limitation, because the vast majority of serious buyers in Queensland start their search on these platforms.</p>

      <p>Private sellers can access the portals through FSBO platforms such as Sell My House Online, For Sale By Owner, or Purple Bricks. These services operate by submitting your listing through their own agent licence, for a flat fee typically ranging from $800 to $2,500 depending on the listing package. You retain control of buyer enquiries and inspections, but the listing appears on the major portals.</p>

      <p>The trade-off is visibility. FSBO-listed properties typically appear lower in search results than agent-listed properties, because the portals prioritise agent-activated premium listings. You also receive less marketing support: no professional negotiator handling enquiries, no vendor management through the campaign, no agent database of buyers who have been looking for a property like yours. These are the less visible things agents do that private sellers rarely account for when calculating the commission saving.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The negotiation reality</h2>
      <p>Direct buyer-seller negotiations are consistently the most difficult part of private sales. When a buyer makes an offer, they are negotiating directly with an emotionally invested seller. Buyers are aware of this. Research from CoreLogic and various academic studies into Australian private sales consistently finds that buyers apply larger discounts when negotiating directly with owners than when dealing with an agent buffer. The agent's role as a neutral intermediary does more to protect the sale price than most sellers appreciate before they experience direct negotiations themselves.</p>

      <p>The practical challenge is that every conversation about price with a buyer is a negotiation, and you are doing it without professional training, real-time comparable sales data, or knowledge of the buyer's financial position and motivation. A skilled buyers' agent on the other side of the table will often identify seller motivation within the first conversation and use it. If you indicate urgency, financial pressure, or emotional attachment, an experienced buyer or their representative will use that information systematically.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the research shows about private sale prices</h2>
      <p>The empirical evidence on private sale outcomes in Australia is not favourable to the FSBO approach. Research by CoreLogic, the Real Estate Institute of Queensland, and independent academic studies consistently finds that privately sold properties achieve lower median prices than comparable agent-sold properties, frequently by a margin that exceeds typical commission costs. A 2022 REIQ study found that in Queensland, properties sold privately achieved approximately 4 to 7 per cent less than comparable agent-sold properties after controlling for location, property type, and market conditions.</p>

      <p>This does not mean every private seller achieves a lower price. Some do not. But the average outcome suggests the commission saving is often illusory when the achieved price difference is factored in. On a $1.2 million property, a 5 per cent shortfall is $60,000. The commission saved might be $25,000. The net outcome is a $35,000 loss.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When private sale makes sense</h2>
      <p>Private sales do make sense in specific circumstances. If you have a buyer already identified, such as a neighbour who has approached you, a family member purchasing the property, or an existing tenant, a private sale avoids the need for a full marketing campaign and an agent's commission. Your solicitor can still manage the contract and conveyancing, and you save the campaign costs along with the commission.</p>

      <p>If you have a background in sales, negotiation, or property, and have access to comparable sales data through a valuer, a private sale may suit you better than the average seller. The skills that make agents effective at achieving strong prices are not unique to the industry.</p>

      <p>Private sale also makes sense when the property is straightforward, well priced, and demand is strong enough that multiple buyers are likely to make contact regardless of how you market it. In very hot markets with low stock and high demand, a well-priced property on the major portals will find buyers with or without an agent. The question is whether an agent can leverage that competition into a materially higher price than you would achieve on your own.</p>

      <p>For most sellers in Brisbane's inner east, the combination of pricing complexity, access limitations, legal requirements, and negotiation dynamics means that agent-sold outcomes consistently outperform FSBO outcomes. But the honest assessment depends on your specific circumstances, and the calculation is worth doing properly before you decide.</p>

